<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="359" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,153,179]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is named after Mr. Chunhao Wang (
<collectingRegion box="[931,1017,153,180]" country="China" name="Beijing" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Beijing</collectingRegion>
) for his kind help to the first author’s study on skipper butterflies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="359" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,224,251]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Discussion.</emphasis>
This new species is only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[814,862,225,251]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">type</typeStatus>
locality, Cenwanglaoshan NNR (
<figureCitation box="[1242,1326,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1005,1030]" captionTargetBox="[252,1335,174,986]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[252,1335,174,986]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 17. Habitat of Pedesta wangi sp. nov. in Cenwanglaoshan NNR of Guangxi. Photographed by Guoxi Xue. Photos of the specimen were taken immediately after capture." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3548628" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3548628/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). All four males were captured by the side of a road inside the reserve. But no more specimens were found during the collecting trip to the same place in June of 2017. Its voltinism and relative bionomic information need further study.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">
Based upon examined specimens and the records in 
<bibRefCitation author="Inayoshi, Y." box="[794,976,333,359]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" refId="ref3259" refString="Inayoshi, Y. (2019) A check list of butterflies in Indo-China, chiefly from Thailand, Laos &amp; Vietnam. Available from: http: // yutaka. it-n. jp / hes / 91247001. html (accessed 2 February 2019)" type="url" year="2019">Inayoshi (2019)</bibRefCitation>
, a distribution map of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Huang &amp; Zhan" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[1234,1387,334,359]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xiaoqingae">
<emphasis box="[1234,1387,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">P. xiaoqingae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xue &amp; Li &amp; Zhu &amp; Lu &amp; Li &amp; Zheng" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,247,370,395]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wangi">
<emphasis box="[151,247,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">P. wangi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is provided (
<figureCitation box="[394,478,369,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1979,2004]" captionTargetBox="[295,1291,1080,1960]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[295,1291,1080,1960]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 18. Distribution map of Pedesta wangi sp. nov. and P. xiaoqingae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3548630" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3548630/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). It shows that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Huang &amp; Zhan" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[648,799,370,395]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xiaoqingae">
<emphasis box="[648,799,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">P. xiaoqingae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed from Nanling Mountains, Hainan Island to 
<collectingCountry box="[151,246,405,431]" name="Vietnam" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
and central 
<collectingCountry box="[382,439,405,431]" name="Laos" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Laos</collectingCountry>
, whereas the 
<typeStatus box="[589,637,405,431]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xue &amp; Li &amp; Zhu &amp; Lu &amp; Li &amp; Zheng" authorityYear="2019" box="[764,859,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wangi">
<emphasis box="[764,859,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">P. wangi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is located at the southeast edge of Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau and isolated from the distribution range of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Huang &amp; Zhan" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[735,888,442,467]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xiaoqingae">
<emphasis box="[735,888,442,467]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">P. xiaoqingae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Guangxi Basin. So we infer that geographic isolation played a very important role during the speciation of the cryptic species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xue &amp; Li &amp; Zhu &amp; Lu &amp; Li &amp; Zheng" authorityYear="2019" box="[1065,1160,478,503]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wangi">
<emphasis box="[1065,1160,478,503]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">P. wangi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
